[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Security (blast-radius containment)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** Prerequisites table and the AWS Implementation section.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe specifies KMS encryption at the service level (SSE-KMS for S3, KMS for SageMaker volumes) but does not specify whether the same key is used across all data classes or whether different keys are used per data class. For a single-clinic deployment, one key is fine. For a multi-clinic or health-system deployment, the conventional pattern is per-data-class keys (one for raw exports, one for engineered features, one for model artifacts, one for forecast outputs) so a compromised key reveals only one stage of the pipeline. The recipe doesn't have to mandate this for a "Simple" recipe, but a one-sentence note in the Honest Take or the Why-This-Isn't-Production-Ready section would orient the reader.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add a sentence to "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" → "IAM resource scoping" paragraph or add a new short paragraph on "KMS key separation": "For multi-clinic deployments, use a separate customer-managed KMS key per data class (raw exports, engineered features, model artifacts, forecast outputs) so a compromised key reveals only one pipeline stage, not the whole pipeline."
