[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Expert:** Architecture (claims-vs-evidence discipline)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** "Expected Results" section, "Performance benchmarks" table. The current text reads: "Performance benchmarks for typical primary care appointment forecasting (illustrative; `<!-- TODO: verify benchmarks against published references or internal data -->`):"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe contains a visible inline TODO comment in the published prose flagging that the benchmark numbers (5–10% MAE for 1-week horizon, 8–15% MAPE for 4-week horizon, 75–85% prediction-interval coverage, 30–90s Prophet training, 15–45 min DeepAR training on `ml.c5.2xlarge`) have not been verified against published references or internal data. The numbers are individually plausible (Prophet on stable healthcare time series typically lands in the 5–15% MAPE range; DeepAR training on 50 clinics with 3 years of daily data on a c5.2xlarge is plausible at 15–45 min) but the recipe explicitly flags them as unverified. Shipping a recipe with an unresolved TODO inline in the published table is a discipline issue, not a correctness issue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Either (a) resolve the TODO by citing a published reference (a few candidates exist in the operations-research and healthcare-analytics literature), an AWS reference (the Amazon SageMaker DeepAR documentation has approximate training-time guidance), or internal validation data; or (b) reframe the table as "Order-of-magnitude expectations, not validated benchmarks" and remove the TODO comment. Preferred fix is (a).
